user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following OS_FDGetInfo code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 8.13.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 is A pointer should point to a const-qualified type whenever possible.

</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of OS_FDGetInfo.
```c
int32 OS_FDGetInfo(osal_id_t filedes, OS_file_prop_t *fd_prop)
{
    OS_common_record_t *record;
    OS_object_token_t   token;
    int32               return_code;

    /* Check parameters */
    OS_CHECK_POINTER(fd_prop);

    memset(fd_prop, 0, sizeof(OS_file_prop_t));

    /* Check Parameters */
    return_code = OS_ObjectIdGetById(OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE, filedes, &token);
    if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        record = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_global_stream_table, token);

        if (record->name_entry != NULL)
        {
            strncpy(fd_prop->Path, record->name_entry, sizeof(fd_prop->Path) - 1);
        }
        fd_prop->User    = record->creator;
        fd_prop->IsValid = true;

        OS_ObjectIdRelease(&token);
    }

    return return_code;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The local pointer 'record' is only used to read fields (record->name_entry, record->creator) and is not modified. According to MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 it should be declared to point to a const-qualified type (e.g. const OS_common_record_t *record). Declaring it non-const here unnecessarily permits modification and thus violates the rule.
</scenario>
